  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 3e1cd92da80c7495a8fe7eb91fa80c2f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Crocus
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::Plants.PlantData
  displayName: Crocus
  audioClip: {fileID: 8300000, guid: 3648001bbb8fec14dbf73cda316983d5, type: 3}
  environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  poem:
    text: "The Crocus's Soliloquy\n\nDown in my solitude under the snow, \nWhere
      nothing cheering can reach me; \nHere, without light to see how to grow, \nI'll
      trust to nature to teach me. \nSoon as the frost will get out of my bed, \nFrom
      this cold dungeon to free me \n,I will peer up with my little bright head;
      \nAll will be joyful to see me. \nMany, perhaps, from so simple a flower \nThis
      little lesson may borrow \u2014 \nPatient to-day, through its gloomiest hour,
      \nWe come out the brighter to-morrow.\n\n\u2014 Hannah Flagg Gould"
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  contextInfos:
  - text: '## Crocus, Greek Mythology

      Crocus was a young mortal, who was in
      love with the Nymph Smilax. Either the love was not returned, or no love was
      possible between mortal and nymph, leading to the gods taking pity upon Crocus,
      turning him into the saffron flower as a relief for his grief.'
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  - text: "## Crocus, Minoans\nThe Minoans were a Bronze Age civilization centered
      on Crete and the Cyclades (c. 2000\u20131400 BCE), known for their palace complexes,
      vivid frescoes, and far-reaching Aegean trade. Among their art, the crocus
      held notable cultural relevance, likely due to the many-layered value of saffron,
      used as dye, medicine, colorant, and possibly a ritual substance, and its consistent
      links to women, animals, and a likely deity, suggesting it was woven deep into
      Minoan myth and identity. Today it survives mainly in their frescoes and pottery.\n\n![[_Die_Fresken_von_Akrotiri_z\xE4hlen_zu_den_spektakul\xE4rsten_Zeugen_der_Bronzezeit.__11.jpg]]\nhttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Saffron_gatherers_(Akrotiri)"
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  - text: "## Frances Allen Harper \u2014 The Crocuses (excerpt)\n\nNot a daffodil
      nor daisy\nHad dared to raise its head;\nNot a fairhaired dandelion\nPeeped
      timid from its bed;\n\nThough a tremor of the winter\nDid shivering through
      them run;\nYet they lifted up their foreheads\nTo greet the vernal sun.\n\nAnd
      the sunbeams gave them welcome,\nAs did the morning air\u2014\nAnd scattered
      o\u2019er their simple robes\nRich tints of beauty rare.\n\nSoon a host of
      lovely flowers\nFrom vales and woodland burst;\nBut in all that fair procession\nThe
      crocuses were first."
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
